I know the books and the David Suchet show occasionally had chase scenes and even the VERY odd gunfight, but NOT IN MURDER ON THE ORIENT EXPRESS! I'm still going to see it out of curiosity and my love for Agatha Christie and the adaptations of her work (especially the bad ones) but right now my highest hopes for the movie is that at least it'll be entertainingly bad.  I really hope I'm wrong. I love Agatha Christie and Kenneth Branagh, and I REALLY want to like this movie, but the trailer did nothing for me.

text: "The director fails to capture the stifling, terrorizing claustrophobia of the coach, making it look all very simple and straight-forward. Even the top shots inside the carriages that he shoots are more distracting, taking an almost detached view of the goings-on below, you wondering what to make of all the heads you see. With the result, the breathtaking scenery is memorable, the mystery less so. Is that why the denouement, weak by any detective movie standards, takes place outside the train - all the passengers lined up on chairs, as if guests of honor at a valedictory event ‚Äì instead of inside of the dining car, where the tension in the book and the 1974 movie was unbearable?" Read the complete review here: http://lifeisacinemahall.com/2017/11/26/murder-on-the-orient-express-review-kenneth-branagh-agatha-christie/

text: Got my reservations about the train....the loco is Americanised: the bell, the deep tone whistle are pretty much alien to European engines: cowcatcher or snow plough?....and why only 4 coaches: baggage and provision car, sleeping car, dining car and lounge car, where does the staff sleep on a three day journey?  Also (my last whinge) the balcony on the last car, I have looked for evidence of this in period photos of coaches of the time and have yet to see an example.  The CGI was all too "Polar Express-ish"...in fact the loco in that movie was far more convincing....Apart from that I enjoyed the cast.
